WY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlu=
a19pZCI6OTk0NjkxfQ/82900c786431f0453cf411e895bb7ce2a05efd416394cda6f934ebb0=
d6d57e26" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" cla=
ss=3D"sdf">reportedly helped him out</a></u> in the past, now finds himself=
 in an interesting legal pickle. In August 2015, while still at
Universal, several years before he was dismissed for making hush money paym=
ents to cover up an old affair, he made a $5 million loan application to th=
e Mohegan Sun Casino, in Connecticut. The application was approved. Then, t=
wo years later, on October 13, 2017, Meyer signed six =E2=80=9Cmarkers=E2=
=80=9D with the casino=E2=80=94checks for $1 million each, made out to Mohe=
gan Sun. That day, he redeemed one of the $1 million checks for chips, and =
the casino retained the other five $1 million checks. Then Meyer went gambl=
ing. =E2=80=9CHe did not win,=E2=80=9D according to a complaint filed by th=
e casino against Meyer, in June, for breach of contract. <br/><br/>In fact,=
 according to the complaint, Meyer lost $5 million gambling that day. The c=
asino then agreed to give Meyer until April 4, 2018, to pay the money he ow=
ed. But when the casino went to cash the checks it still held from Meyer at=
 the bank, all five were returned for insufficient funds. And so on April 2=
6, Meyer and the casino entered into a
<i>new</i> agreement, under which Meyer agreed to a repayment schedule for =
the $5 million he owed. The plan was to pay $60,000 a month between May 1, =
2018, and September 1, 2022, with one final payment of $45,960. The casino =
even agreed to give Meyer a discount, of slightly more than $1.5 million, o=
n the debt if he made the payments on schedule. Meyer also agreed to give t=
he casino 50 percent of any winnings from his gambling at the casino, to be=
 applied to the debt he owed.<br/><br/>Meyer did well, for a while. But in =
October and November 2020, he missed his $60,000 payments, and then paid $1=
20,000 in December 2020. He didn=E2=80=99t make another payment for six mon=
ths, and then paid only $10,000 in June 2021. He then paid $10,000 a month =
between June 2021 and August 2022, and then made monthly payments of $12,50=
0. He stopped making payments altogether on September 1, 2023, still owing =
the casino $2,782,500. According to the complaint, the casino subsequently =
spoke with Meyer
=E2=80=9Con numerous occasions,=E2=80=9D and Meyer =E2=80=9Crepeatedly stat=
ed that he had every intention of paying the balance, but he did not do so.=
=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>That=E2=80=99s how the litigation between Mohegan Sun an=
d Meyer ended up in Superior Court, in New London, Connecticut, where it is=
 still pending. In a court filing on August 9, <b>Brian Spears,</b> Meyer=
=E2=80=99s Southport, Connecticut, lawyer, asked that the judge dismiss the=
 =E2=80=9Cbreach of contract=E2=80=9D claim against Meyer=E2=80=94the only =
count against him=E2=80=94arguing that =E2=80=9CConnecticut prohibits the e=
nforcement of contracts facilitating any type of gambling on credit=E2=80=
=9D and that Connecticut has an =E2=80=9Cancient and deep-rooted=E2=80=9D p=
ublic policy against gambling. He cited a state statute that includes the l=
anguage that =E2=80=9Call contracts to repay any money knowingly lent at th=
e time and place of such game, race, sport or pastime, to any person so gam=
ing, betting or wagering, or to repay any money lent to any person who, at =
such time and place, so pays,
bets or wagers, shall be void.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>If I have this right, Spe=
ars is arguing that we should all go to Mohegan Sun, gamble to our heart=E2=
=80=99s content, lose millions, and we won=E2=80=99t have to pay the money =
we lost using credit because gambling using credit is illegal in Connecticu=
t. Well, that=E2=80=99s a new one. Reached at his office on Wednesday, Spea=
rs declined to comment on the pending litigation.<br/><br/></li><li><i>Trum=
p=E2=80=99s latest financial mess</i>: In many ways, Trump Media &amp; Tech=
nology=E2=80=94the SPAC that merged with <b>Trump</b>=E2=80=99s Truth Socia=
l earlier this year=E2=80=94remains one of the more reliable bellwethers of=
 Trump=E2=80=99s prospects for winning in November, even though the stock s=
houldn=E2=80=99t exist <i>at all</i>, since it is tied to a business with l=
ittle revenue, massive losses, and few users, outside of the former preside=
nt and his lunatic rants. <br/><br/>Anyway, in the last month=E2=80=94rough=
ly coinciding with the R.N.C., the assassination attempt in Butler, Pennsyl=
vania,
and <b>Kamala Harris</b>=E2=80=99s honeymoon period=E2=80=94the DJT (that=
=E2=80=99s the symbol, natch) stock price is down 40 percent.<i> Forty perc=
ent in a month!</i> The Donald=E2=80=99s stock, once worth more than $5 bil=
lion, is now worth around $2.75 billion. That=E2=80=99s not nothing, of cou=
rse, and it=E2=80=99s free money for him. He only has to keep using Truth S=
ocial for his idiotic ramblings to hold up his part of the bargain (althoug=
h he=E2=80=99s now back to using X, at least temporarily, which must have b=
een part of the exchange for the grueling Trump/<b>Musk </b>Spaces conversa=
tion on Monday night). <br/><br/>What explains the ongoing collapse of the =
DJT stock price? Part of it, of course, is the company=E2=80=99s inexplicab=
le market cap of $4.75 billion=E2=80=94a miracle since it=E2=80=99s nothing=
 more than a meme stock. Combine that with poor second-quarter operating re=
sults=E2=80=94the company lost $16.4 million on piddling revenue of <i>$837=
,000</i> (that=E2=80=99s not a typo!), a 30 percent decline from the same q=
uarter in
2023=E2=80=94and the clouds begin to part. Then, of course, there are Trump=
=E2=80=99s increasingly unhinged Truth Social diatribes.=E2=80=9CHas anyone=
 noticed that Kamala CHEATED at the airport?=E2=80=9D he wrote the other da=
y. =E2=80=9CThere was nobody at the plane, and she =E2=80=98A.I.=E2=80=99d=
=E2=80=99 it, and showed a massive =E2=80=98crowd=E2=80=99 of so-called fol=
lowers, BUT THEY DIDN=E2=80=99T EXIST!=E2=80=9D This would be almost humoro=
us if Trump weren=E2=80=99t a former president of the United States with a =
50-50 chance of regaining that office after November. =E2=80=9CHere we have=
 a badly damaged and disturbed person,=E2=80=9D <i>Morning Joe</i>=E2=80=99=
s <b>Mike</b> <b>Barnicle</b> tweeted after that one. <br/><br/>The truth i=
s that Trump Media &amp; Technology is not a sustainable business. It=E2=80=
=99s simply a referendum on Trump=E2=80=99s political future, and a way for=
 his supporters to try to shuffle money to him. As ever, it=E2=80=99s these=
 retail investors who continue to get burned by owning the stock, since it =
is now well off its high of nearly $80 per share. Once a
con artist, always a con artist, I guess=E2=80=A6</li></ul>
